Eventually, John Garand developed the M1 Rifle, now commonly referred to as the Garand, and it was formally adopted by the US Ordnance Department on January 9, 1936. The Sear on this rifle is a Springfield Armory Sear without the weep hole and it retains the majority of its original blue finish with wear on the sharp edges. The Sear Pin retains the majority of its original blued finish on the face. postcontent: If you know what this is, you already think I'm nuts to get rid of it, but I want to fund a new buy.  Jim Rose built this 1911 for Bullseye matches, and it was used a bit, but not too much because my work schedule did not permit.  Seldom did my work permit me time to attend matches.  Jim Rose was a nationally known shooter and gun smith out of Jacksonville, Florida,... a gruff old shit who really knew his way around 1911s and the match circuits.  Twelve times Sunstate Pistol Champion, shot nationally, on and on and on.  He was good, really good, and he built really special (and expensive) pistols, and built them very slowly.  This one is a Jim Rose Bullseye pistol, an Essex with 10XXX serial number,  almost never leaves my safe, but I've found a firearm that interests me, and that interest is more than the money I have available.  So, if you're a match shooter... or a collector... or you simply want to buy this to make money on it, the price is firm, I'm not looking for trades unless it's an interesting rifle. title: For Sale:  Rare collector item Merwin Hulbert & Co 38 caliber revolver from 1880  factory engraved nickle & pearl
location: inland empire Riverside, Inland Empire, California
postcontent:
This Merwin Hulbert pistol with 3 1/2" legth barrel was produced around 1880. It was my grandfathers, grandfathers gun and has been in our family a very long time and possibly from new. It was well optioned from the factory being graced with nickle plating, folding hammer, full factory "punch dot" engraving including an intricate hunting dog scene on the left side panel, jewel color highlights, very rare "GOLD WASH" cylinder, and beautufully finished off with stunning factory authentic "Mother Of Pearl" grips. The top of the barrel rib has the MFG / city / and patent dates. The left side of the frame is marked 38 CAL. This revolver is 100% all original with all it's origial born with parts and has all the matching serial numbers present: on the main frame under the Pearl grip area, on the rear face of the cylinder, on the rear face of the barrel assembly, and stampings on the side of the hammer.  Sights are the factory pinned blade at front of barrel with notch at rear. Condition: Over-all EXCELLENT in appearance retaining it's original nickle finish which is overall bright and shiney with some normal wear for a gun manufactured this age. The case hardened finish on the exposed trigger and hammer is still present. The "Gold Wash" applied originally to the cylinder assembly is still clearly visible but has been worn from all the years of wiping the gun down. Given it's age, one should expect some accidental scratching and misc dings as to be expected. The double action /single action / and first position safety cock all function perfectly and the timing of the action seems perfect as well. The inside of the barrel is shiney and rifeling crisp so it appears to have had an easy life. Grips are fabulous, no cracks at all and nice Pearl coloring. There appears to never have been any corrosion on this fire arm and you would be hard pressed to find one in better condition with more options & features making this a very desireable collectable gun in fantastic shape with all the bells and whisles a true collector could wish for. 
I may consider trades for interesting firearms. I prefer pistols over rifles. Would consider a collectable motorcycle as well or ?
